{
  "answer": "**No works in the Falsafa corpus open with an invocation to a deity or divine figure.**\n\nAfter examining the openings of the most likely candidates—Christian poems by Cynewulf (*Andreas*, *Elene*, *Juliana*), Indic law texts (*Manusmṛti*, *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, *Yama Smṛti*, *Nārada Smṛti*), and Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara*—none begin with a direct address such as \"O Lord,\" \"O God,\" or similar prayerful invocation.[^1][^2][^3][^4][^5][^6][^7] These texts typically commence with narrative introductions (e.g., \"We have heard...\" in Cynewulf) or dialogues among sages (e.g., sages approaching Manu or Yama). While some feature divine elements later or frame sages as quasi-divine, the openings lack invocation.[^8] The corpus prioritizes philosophical and legal discourse over hymnic prologues.",
